{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"Well, it's great to be here."},{"time":1000,"text":"We've heard a lot about the promise of technology, and the peril."},{"time":6000,"text":"I've been quite interested in both."},{"time":8000,"text":"If we could convert 0.03 percent"},{"time":12000,"text":"of the sunlight that falls on the earth into energy,"},{"time":14000,"text":"we could meet all of our projected needs for 2030."},{"time":19000,"text":"We can't do that today because solar panels are heavy,"},{"time":22000,"text":"expensive and very inefficient."},{"time":24000,"text":"There are nano-engineered designs,"},{"time":27000,"text":"which at least have been analyzed theoretically,"},{"time":29000,"text":"that show the potential to be very lightweight,"},{"time":31000,"text":"very inexpensive, very efficient,"},{"time":33000,"text":"and we'd be able to actually provide all of our energy needs in this renewable way."},{"time":37000,"text":"Nano-engineered fuel cells"},{"time":39000,"text":"could provide the energy where it's needed."},{"time":42000,"text":"That's a key trend, which is decentralization,"},{"time":44000,"text":"moving from centralized nuclear power plants and"},{"time":47000,"text":"liquid natural gas tankers"},{"time":49000,"text":"to decentralized resources that are environmentally more friendly,"},{"time":53000,"text":"a lot more efficient"},{"time":56000,"text":"and capable and safe from disruption."}]},{"cues":[{"time":60000,"text":"Bono spoke very eloquently,"},{"time":62000,"text":"that we have the tools, for the first time,"},{"time":66000,"text":"to address age-old problems of disease and poverty."},{"time":70000,"text":"Most regions of the world are moving in that direction."},{"time":74000,"text":"In 1990, in East Asia and the Pacific region,"},{"time":78000,"text":"there were 500 million people living in poverty --"},{"time":80000,"text":"that number now is under 200 million."},{"time":83000,"text":"The World Bank projects by 2011, it will be under 20 million,"},{"time":86000,"text":"which is a reduction of 95 percent."},{"time":89000,"text":"I did enjoy Bono's comment"},{"time":92000,"text":"linking Haight-Ashbury to Silicon Valley."},{"time":96000,"text":"Being from the Massachusetts high-tech community myself,"},{"time":99000,"text":"I'd point out that we were hippies also in the 1960s,"},{"time":104000,"text":"although we hung around Harvard Square."},{"time":107000,"text":"But we do have the potential to overcome disease and poverty,"},{"time":112000,"text":"and I'm going to talk about those issues, if we have the will."}]},{"cues":[{"time":115000,"text":"Kevin Kelly talked about the acceleration of technology."},{"time":118000,"text":"That's been a strong interest of mine,"},{"time":121000,"text":"and a theme that I've developed for some 30 years."},{"time":124000,"text":"I realized that my technologies had to make sense when I finished a project."},{"time":129000,"text":"That invariably, the world was a different place"},{"time":132000,"text":"when I would introduce a technology."},{"time":134000,"text":"And, I noticed that most inventions fail,"},{"time":136000,"text":"not because the R&amp;D department can't get it to work --"},{"time":139000,"text":"if you look at most business plans, they will actually succeed"},{"time":142000,"text":"if given the opportunity to build what they say they're going to build --"},{"time":146000,"text":"and 90 percent of those projects or more will fail, because the timing is wrong --"},{"time":149000,"text":"not all the enabling factors will be in place when they're needed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":152000,"text":"So I began to be an ardent student of technology trends,"},{"time":156000,"text":"and track where technology would be at different points in time,"},{"time":159000,"text":"and began to build the mathematical models of that."},{"time":162000,"text":"It's kind of taken on a life of its own."},{"time":164000,"text":"I've got a group of 10 people that work with me to gather data"},{"time":167000,"text":"on key measures of technology in many different areas, and we build models."},{"time":172000,"text":"And you'll hear people say, well, we can't predict the future."},{"time":175000,"text":"And if you ask me,"},{"time":177000,"text":"will the price of Google be higher or lower than it is today three years from now,"},{"time":180000,"text":"that's very hard to say."},{"time":182000,"text":"Will WiMax CDMA G3"},{"time":185000,"text":"be the wireless standard three years from now? That's hard to say."},{"time":187000,"text":"But if you ask me, what will it cost"},{"time":189000,"text":"for one MIPS of computing in 2010,"},{"time":192000,"text":"or the cost to sequence a base pair of DNA in 2012,"},{"time":195000,"text":"or the cost of sending a megabyte of data wirelessly in 2014,"},{"time":199000,"text":"it turns out that those are very predictable."}]},{"cues":[{"time":202000,"text":"There are remarkably smooth exponential curves"},{"time":204000,"text":"that govern price performance, capacity, bandwidth."},{"time":207000,"text":"And I'm going to show you a small sample of this,"},{"time":209000,"text":"but there's really a theoretical reason"},{"time":211000,"text":"why technology develops in an exponential fashion."},{"time":216000,"text":"And a lot of people, when they think about the future, think about it linearly."},{"time":218000,"text":"They think they're going to continue"},{"time":220000,"text":"to develop a problem"},{"time":222000,"text":"or address a problem using today's tools,"},{"time":225000,"text":"at today's pace of progress,"},{"time":227000,"text":"and fail to take into consideration this exponential growth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":231000,"text":"The Genome Project was a controversial project in 1990."},{"time":234000,"text":"We had our best Ph.D. students,"},{"time":236000,"text":"our most advanced equipment around the world,"},{"time":238000,"text":"we got 1/10,000th of the project done,"},{"time":240000,"text":"so how're we going to get this done in 15 years?"},{"time":242000,"text":"And 10 years into the project,"},{"time":246000,"text":"the skeptics were still going strong -- says, \"You're two-thirds through this project,"},{"time":248000,"text":"and you've managed to only sequence"},{"time":250000,"text":"a very tiny percentage of the whole genome.\""},{"time":253000,"text":"But it's the nature of exponential growth"},{"time":255000,"text":"that once it reaches the knee of the curve, it explodes."},{"time":257000,"text":"Most of the project was done in the last"},{"time":259000,"text":"few years of the project."},{"time":261000,"text":"It took us 15 years to sequence HIV --"},{"time":263000,"text":"we sequenced SARS in 31 days."},{"time":265000,"text":"So we are gaining the potential to overcome these problems."}]},{"cues":[{"time":269000,"text":"I'm going to show you just a few examples"},{"time":271000,"text":"of how pervasive this phenomena is."},{"time":274000,"text":"The actual paradigm-shift rate, the rate of adopting new ideas,"},{"time":278000,"text":"is doubling every decade, according to our models."},{"time":281000,"text":"These are all logarithmic graphs,"},{"time":284000,"text":"so as you go up the levels it represents, generally multiplying by factor of 10 or 100."},{"time":287000,"text":"It took us half a century to adopt the telephone,"},{"time":290000,"text":"the first virtual-reality technology."},{"time":293000,"text":"Cell phones were adopted in about eight years."},{"time":295000,"text":"If you put different communication technologies"},{"time":298000,"text":"on this logarithmic graph,"},{"time":300000,"text":"television, radio, telephone"},{"time":302000,"text":"were adopted in decades."},{"time":304000,"text":"Recent technologies -- like the PC, the web, cell phones --"},{"time":307000,"text":"were under a decade."},{"time":309000,"text":"Now this is an interesting chart,"},{"time":311000,"text":"and this really gets at the fundamental reason why"},{"time":313000,"text":"an evolutionary process -- and both biology and technology are evolutionary processes --"},{"time":317000,"text":"accelerate."},{"time":319000,"text":"They work through interaction -- they create a capability,"},{"time":322000,"text":"and then it uses that capability to bring on the next stage."}]},{"cues":[{"time":325000,"text":"So the first step in biological evolution,"},{"time":328000,"text":"the evolution of DNA -- actually it was RNA came first --"},{"time":330000,"text":"took billions of years,"},{"time":332000,"text":"but then evolution used that information-processing backbone"},{"time":335000,"text":"to bring on the next stage."},{"time":337000,"text":"So the Cambrian Explosion, when all the body plans of the animals were evolved,"},{"time":340000,"text":"took only 10 million years. It was 200 times faster."},{"time":344000,"text":"And then evolution used those body plans"},{"time":346000,"text":"to evolve higher cognitive functions,"},{"time":348000,"text":"and biological evolution kept accelerating."},{"time":350000,"text":"It's an inherent nature of an evolutionary process."},{"time":353000,"text":"So Homo sapiens, the first technology-creating species,"},{"time":356000,"text":"the species that combined a cognitive function"},{"time":358000,"text":"with an opposable appendage --"},{"time":360000,"text":"and by the way, chimpanzees don't really have a very good opposable thumb --"},{"time":364000,"text":"so we could actually manipulate our environment with a power grip"},{"time":366000,"text":"and fine motor coordination,"},{"time":368000,"text":"and use our mental models to actually change the world"},{"time":370000,"text":"and bring on technology."}]},{"cues":[{"time":372000,"text":"But anyway, the evolution of our species took hundreds of thousands of years,"},{"time":375000,"text":"and then working through interaction,"},{"time":377000,"text":"evolution used, essentially,"},{"time":379000,"text":"the technology-creating species to bring on the next stage,"},{"time":382000,"text":"which were the first steps in technological evolution."},{"time":385000,"text":"And the first step took tens of thousands of years --"},{"time":388000,"text":"stone tools, fire, the wheel -- kept accelerating."},{"time":391000,"text":"We always used then the latest generation of technology"},{"time":393000,"text":"to create the next generation."},{"time":395000,"text":"Printing press took a century to be adopted;"},{"time":397000,"text":"the first computers were designed pen-on-paper -- now we use computers."},{"time":401000,"text":"And we've had a continual acceleration of this process."}]},{"cues":[{"time":404000,"text":"Now by the way, if you look at this on a linear graph, it looks like everything has just happened,"},{"time":407000,"text":"but some observer says, \"Well, Kurzweil just put points on this graph"},{"time":413000,"text":"that fall on that straight line.\""},{"time":415000,"text":"So, I took 15 different lists from key thinkers,"},{"time":418000,"text":"like the Encyclopedia Britannica, the Museum of Natural History, Carl Sagan's Cosmic Calendar"},{"time":422000,"text":"on the same -- and these people were not trying to make my point;"},{"time":425000,"text":"these were just lists in reference works,"},{"time":427000,"text":"and I think that's what they thought the key events were"},{"time":430000,"text":"in biological evolution and technological evolution."},{"time":433000,"text":"And again, it forms the same straight line. You have a little bit of thickening in the line"},{"time":436000,"text":"because people do have disagreements, what the key points are,"},{"time":439000,"text":"there's differences of opinion when agriculture started,"},{"time":441000,"text":"or how long the Cambrian Explosion took."},{"time":444000,"text":"But you see a very clear trend."},{"time":446000,"text":"There's a basic, profound acceleration of this evolutionary process."},{"time":451000,"text":"Information technologies double their capacity, price performance, bandwidth,"},{"time":456000,"text":"every year."},{"time":458000,"text":"And that's a very profound explosion of exponential growth."},{"time":462000,"text":"A personal experience, when I was at MIT --"},{"time":464000,"text":"computer taking up about the size of this room,"},{"time":466000,"text":"less powerful than the computer in your cell phone."},{"time":471000,"text":"But Moore's Law, which is very often identified with this exponential growth,"},{"time":475000,"text":"is just one example of many, because it's basically"},{"time":477000,"text":"a property of the evolutionary process of technology."}]},{"cues":[{"time":482000,"text":"I put 49 famous computers on this logarithmic graph --"},{"time":485000,"text":"by the way, a straight line on a logarithmic graph is exponential growth --"},{"time":489000,"text":"that's another exponential."},{"time":491000,"text":"It took us three years to double our price performance of computing in 1900,"},{"time":494000,"text":"two years in the middle; we're now doubling it every one year."},{"time":498000,"text":"And that's exponential growth through five different paradigms."},{"time":501000,"text":"Moore's Law was just the last part of that,"},{"time":503000,"text":"where we were shrinking transistors on an integrated circuit,"},{"time":506000,"text":"but we had electro-mechanical calculators,"},{"time":509000,"text":"relay-based computers that cracked the German Enigma Code,"},{"time":511000,"text":"vacuum tubes in the 1950s predicted the election of Eisenhower,"},{"time":515000,"text":"discreet transistors used in the first space flights"},{"time":518000,"text":"and then Moore's Law."},{"time":520000,"text":"Every time one paradigm ran out of steam,"},{"time":522000,"text":"another paradigm came out of left field to continue the exponential growth."},{"time":525000,"text":"They were shrinking vacuum tubes, making them smaller and smaller."},{"time":528000,"text":"That hit a wall. They couldn't shrink them and keep the vacuum."},{"time":531000,"text":"Whole different paradigm -- transistors came out of the woodwork."},{"time":533000,"text":"In fact, when we see the end of the line for a particular paradigm,"},{"time":536000,"text":"it creates research pressure to create the next paradigm."},{"time":540000,"text":"And because we've been predicting the end of Moore's Law"},{"time":543000,"text":"for quite a long time -- the first prediction said 2002, until now it says 2022."},{"time":546000,"text":"But by the teen years,"},{"time":549000,"text":"the features of transistors will be a few atoms in width,"},{"time":552000,"text":"and we won't be able to shrink them any more."},{"time":554000,"text":"That'll be the end of Moore's Law, but it won't be the end of"},{"time":557000,"text":"the exponential growth of computing, because chips are flat."},{"time":559000,"text":"We live in a three-dimensional world; we might as well use the third dimension."},{"time":562000,"text":"We will go into the third dimension"},{"time":564000,"text":"and there's been tremendous progress, just in the last few years,"},{"time":567000,"text":"of getting three-dimensional, self-organizing molecular circuits to work."},{"time":571000,"text":"We'll have those ready well before Moore's Law runs out of steam."},{"time":578000,"text":"Supercomputers -- same thing."},{"time":581000,"text":"Processor performance on Intel chips,"},{"time":584000,"text":"the average price of a transistor --"},{"time":587000,"text":"1968, you could buy one transistor for a dollar."},{"time":590000,"text":"You could buy 10 million in 2002."}]},{"cues":[{"time":593000,"text":"It's pretty remarkable how smooth"},{"time":596000,"text":"an exponential process that is."},{"time":598000,"text":"I mean, you'd think this is the result of some tabletop experiment,"},{"time":602000,"text":"but this is the result of worldwide chaotic behavior --"},{"time":605000,"text":"countries accusing each other of dumping products,"},{"time":607000,"text":"IPOs, bankruptcies, marketing programs."},{"time":609000,"text":"You would think it would be a very erratic process,"},{"time":612000,"text":"and you have a very smooth"},{"time":614000,"text":"outcome of this chaotic process."},{"time":616000,"text":"Just as we can't predict"},{"time":618000,"text":"what one molecule in a gas will do --"},{"time":620000,"text":"it's hopeless to predict a single molecule --"},{"time":623000,"text":"yet we can predict the properties of the whole gas,"},{"time":625000,"text":"using thermodynamics, very accurately."},{"time":628000,"text":"It's the same thing here. We can't predict any particular project,"},{"time":631000,"text":"but the result of this whole worldwide,"},{"time":633000,"text":"chaotic, unpredictable activity of competition"},{"time":638000,"text":"and the evolutionary process of technology is very predictable."},{"time":641000,"text":"And we can predict these trends far into the future."},{"time":646000,"text":"Unlike Gertrude Stein's roses,"},{"time":648000,"text":"it's not the case that a transistor is a transistor."},{"time":650000,"text":"As we make them smaller and less expensive,"},{"time":652000,"text":"the electrons have less distance to travel."},{"time":654000,"text":"They're faster, so you've got exponential growth in the speed of transistors,"},{"time":658000,"text":"so the cost of a cycle of one transistor"},{"time":662000,"text":"has been coming down with a halving rate of 1.1 years."},{"time":665000,"text":"You add other forms of innovation and processor design,"},{"time":668000,"text":"you get a doubling of price performance of computing every one year."}]},{"cues":[{"time":672000,"text":"And that's basically deflation --"},{"time":675000,"text":"50 percent deflation."},{"time":677000,"text":"And it's not just computers. I mean, it's true of DNA sequencing;"},{"time":680000,"text":"it's true of brain scanning;"},{"time":682000,"text":"it's true of the World Wide Web. I mean, anything that we can quantify,"},{"time":684000,"text":"we have hundreds of different measurements"},{"time":687000,"text":"of different, information-related measurements --"},{"time":690000,"text":"capacity, adoption rates --"},{"time":692000,"text":"and they basically double every 12, 13, 15 months,"},{"time":695000,"text":"depending on what you're looking at."},{"time":697000,"text":"In terms of price performance, that's a 40 to 50 percent deflation rate."},{"time":702000,"text":"And economists have actually started worrying about that. \n"},{"time":704000,"text":"We had deflation during the Depression,"},{"time":706000,"text":"but that was collapse of the money supply,"},{"time":708000,"text":"collapse of consumer confidence, a completely different phenomena."},{"time":711000,"text":"This is due to greater productivity,"},{"time":714000,"text":"but the economist says, \"But there's no way you're going to be able to keep up with that."},{"time":716000,"text":"If you have 50 percent deflation, people may increase their volume"},{"time":719000,"text":"30, 40 percent, but they won't keep up with it.\""},{"time":721000,"text":"But what we're actually seeing is that"},{"time":723000,"text":"we actually more than keep up with it."},{"time":725000,"text":"We've had 28 percent per year compounded growth in dollars"},{"time":728000,"text":"in information technology over the last 50 years."},{"time":731000,"text":"I mean, people didn't build iPods for 10,000 dollars 10 years ago."},{"time":735000,"text":"As the price performance makes new applications feasible,"},{"time":738000,"text":"new applications come to the market."},{"time":740000,"text":"And this is a very widespread phenomena."},{"time":743000,"text":"Magnetic data storage --"},{"time":745000,"text":"that's not Moore's Law, it's shrinking magnetic spots,"},{"time":748000,"text":"different engineers, different companies, same exponential process."}]},{"cues":[{"time":752000,"text":"A key revolution is that we're understanding our own biology"},{"time":756000,"text":"in these information terms."},{"time":758000,"text":"We're understanding the software programs"},{"time":760000,"text":"that make our body run."},{"time":762000,"text":"These were evolved in very different times --"},{"time":764000,"text":"we'd like to actually change those programs."},{"time":766000,"text":"One little software program, called the fat insulin receptor gene,"},{"time":768000,"text":"basically says, \"Hold onto every calorie,"},{"time":770000,"text":"because the next hunting season may not work out so well.\""},{"time":774000,"text":"That was in the interests of the species tens of thousands of years ago."},{"time":777000,"text":"We'd like to actually turn that program off."},{"time":780000,"text":"They tried that in animals, and these mice ate ravenously"},{"time":783000,"text":"and remained slim and got the health benefits of being slim."},{"time":785000,"text":"They didn't get diabetes; they didn't get heart disease;"},{"time":788000,"text":"they lived 20 percent longer; they got the health benefits of caloric restriction"},{"time":791000,"text":"without the restriction."},{"time":793000,"text":"Four or five pharmaceutical companies have noticed this,"},{"time":796000,"text":"felt that would be"},{"time":799000,"text":"interesting drug for the human market,"},{"time":802000,"text":"and that's just one of the 30,000 genes"},{"time":804000,"text":"that affect our biochemistry."}]},{"cues":[{"time":807000,"text":"We were evolved in an era where it wasn't in the interests of people"},{"time":810000,"text":"at the age of most people at this conference, like myself,"},{"time":813000,"text":"to live much longer, because we were using up the precious resources"},{"time":817000,"text":"which were better deployed towards the children"},{"time":818000,"text":"and those caring for them."},{"time":820000,"text":"So, life -- long lifespans --"},{"time":822000,"text":"like, that is to say, much more than 30 --"},{"time":824000,"text":"weren't selected for,"},{"time":827000,"text":"but we are learning to actually manipulate"},{"time":830000,"text":"and change these software programs"},{"time":832000,"text":"through the biotechnology revolution."},{"time":834000,"text":"For example, we can inhibit genes now with RNA interference."},{"time":838000,"text":"There are exciting new forms of gene therapy"},{"time":840000,"text":"that overcome the problem of placing the genetic material"},{"time":842000,"text":"in the right place on the chromosome."},{"time":844000,"text":"There's actually a -- for the first time now,"},{"time":847000,"text":"something going to human trials, that actually cures pulmonary hypertension --"},{"time":850000,"text":"a fatal disease -- using gene therapy."},{"time":853000,"text":"So we'll have not just designer babies, but designer baby boomers."},{"time":856000,"text":"And this technology is also accelerating."},{"time":859000,"text":"It cost 10 dollars per base pair in 1990,"},{"time":862000,"text":"then a penny in 2000."},{"time":864000,"text":"It's now under a 10th of a cent."},{"time":866000,"text":"The amount of genetic data --"},{"time":868000,"text":"basically this shows that smooth exponential growth"},{"time":871000,"text":"doubled every year,"},{"time":873000,"text":"enabling the genome project to be completed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":876000,"text":"Another major revolution: the communications revolution."},{"time":879000,"text":"The price performance, bandwidth, capacity of communications measured many different ways;"},{"time":884000,"text":"wired, wireless is growing exponentially."},{"time":887000,"text":"The Internet has been doubling in power and continues to,"},{"time":890000,"text":"measured many different ways."},{"time":892000,"text":"This is based on the number of hosts."}]},{"cues":[{"time":894000,"text":"Miniaturization -- we're shrinking the size of technology"},{"time":896000,"text":"at an exponential rate,"},{"time":898000,"text":"both wired and wireless."},{"time":900000,"text":"These are some designs from Eric Drexler's book --"},{"time":904000,"text":"which we're now showing are feasible"},{"time":906000,"text":"with super-computing simulations,"},{"time":908000,"text":"where actually there are scientists building"},{"time":910000,"text":"molecule-scale robots."},{"time":912000,"text":"One has one that actually walks with a surprisingly human-like gait,"},{"time":914000,"text":"that's built out of molecules."},{"time":917000,"text":"There are little machines doing things in experimental bases."},{"time":921000,"text":"The most exciting opportunity"},{"time":924000,"text":"is actually to go inside the human body"},{"time":926000,"text":"and perform therapeutic and diagnostic functions."},{"time":929000,"text":"And this is less futuristic than it may sound."},{"time":931000,"text":"These things have already been done in animals."}]},{"cues":[{"time":933000,"text":"There's one nano-engineered device that cures type 1 diabetes. It's blood cell-sized."},{"time":937000,"text":"They put tens of thousands of these"},{"time":939000,"text":"in the blood cell -- they tried this in rats --"},{"time":941000,"text":"it lets insulin out in a controlled fashion,"},{"time":943000,"text":"and actually cures type 1 diabetes."},{"time":945000,"text":"What you're watching is a design"},{"time":948000,"text":"of a robotic red blood cell,"},{"time":950000,"text":"and it does bring up the issue that our biology"},{"time":952000,"text":"is actually very sub-optimal,"},{"time":954000,"text":"even though it's remarkable in its intricacy."},{"time":957000,"text":"Once we understand its principles of operation,"},{"time":960000,"text":"and the pace with which we are reverse-engineering biology is accelerating,"},{"time":964000,"text":"we can actually design these things to be"},{"time":966000,"text":"thousands of times more capable."},{"time":968000,"text":"An analysis of this respirocyte, designed by Rob Freitas,"},{"time":973000,"text":"indicates if you replace 10 percent of your red blood cells with these robotic versions,"},{"time":976000,"text":"you could do an Olympic sprint for 15 minutes without taking a breath."},{"time":979000,"text":"You could sit at the bottom of your pool for four hours --"},{"time":982000,"text":"so, \"Honey, I'm in the pool,\" will take on a whole new meaning."},{"time":986000,"text":"It will be interesting to see what we do in our Olympic trials."},{"time":988000,"text":"Presumably we'll ban them,"},{"time":990000,"text":"but then we'll have the specter of teenagers in their high schools gyms"},{"time":992000,"text":"routinely out-performing the Olympic athletes."},{"time":997000,"text":"Freitas has a design for a robotic white blood cell."},{"time":1000000,"text":"These are 2020-circa scenarios,"},{"time":1004000,"text":"but they're not as futuristic as it may sound."},{"time":1006000,"text":"There are four major conferences on building blood cell-sized devices;"},{"time":1010000,"text":"there are many experiments in animals."},{"time":1012000,"text":"There's actually one going into human trial,"},{"time":1014000,"text":"so this is feasible technology."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1018000,"text":"If we come back to our exponential growth of computing,"},{"time":1020000,"text":"1,000 dollars of computing is now somewhere between an insect and a mouse brain."},{"time":1023000,"text":"It will intersect human intelligence"},{"time":1026000,"text":"in terms of capacity in the 2020s,"},{"time":1029000,"text":"but that'll be the hardware side of the equation."},{"time":1031000,"text":"Where will we get the software?"},{"time":1033000,"text":"Well, it turns out we can see inside the human brain,"},{"time":1035000,"text":"and in fact not surprisingly,"},{"time":1037000,"text":"the spatial and temporal resolution of brain scanning is doubling every year."},{"time":1041000,"text":"And with the new generation of scanning tools,"},{"time":1043000,"text":"for the first time we can actually see"},{"time":1045000,"text":"individual inter-neural fibers"},{"time":1047000,"text":"and see them processing and signaling in real time --"},{"time":1050000,"text":"but then the question is, OK, we can get this data now,"},{"time":1052000,"text":"but can we understand it?"},{"time":1054000,"text":"Doug Hofstadter wonders, well, maybe our intelligence"},{"time":1057000,"text":"just isn't great enough to understand our intelligence,"},{"time":1060000,"text":"and if we were smarter, well, then our brains would be that much more complicated,"},{"time":1063000,"text":"and we'd never catch up to it."},{"time":1066000,"text":"It turns out that we can understand it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1069000,"text":"This is a block diagram of"},{"time":1072000,"text":"a model and simulation of the human auditory cortex"},{"time":1076000,"text":"that actually works quite well --"},{"time":1078000,"text":"in applying psychoacoustic tests, gets very similar results to human auditory perception."},{"time":1082000,"text":"There's another simulation of the cerebellum --"},{"time":1085000,"text":"that's more than half the neurons in the brain --"},{"time":1087000,"text":"again, works very similarly to human skill formation."},{"time":1091000,"text":"This is at an early stage, but you can show"},{"time":1094000,"text":"with the exponential growth of the amount of information about the brain"},{"time":1097000,"text":"and the exponential improvement"},{"time":1099000,"text":"in the resolution of brain scanning,"},{"time":1101000,"text":"we will succeed in reverse-engineering the human brain"},{"time":1104000,"text":"by the 2020s."},{"time":1106000,"text":"We've already had very good models and simulation of about 15 regions"},{"time":1109000,"text":"out of the several hundred."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1112000,"text":"All of this is driving"},{"time":1114000,"text":"exponentially growing economic progress."},{"time":1116000,"text":"We've had productivity go from 30 dollars to 150 dollars per hour"},{"time":1121000,"text":"of labor in the last 50 years."},{"time":1123000,"text":"E-commerce has been growing exponentially. It's now a trillion dollars."},{"time":1126000,"text":"You might wonder, well, wasn't there a boom and a bust?"},{"time":1128000,"text":"That was strictly a capital-markets phenomena."},{"time":1130000,"text":"Wall Street noticed that this was a revolutionary technology, which it was,"},{"time":1134000,"text":"but then six months later, when it hadn't revolutionized all business models,"},{"time":1137000,"text":"they figured, well, that was wrong,"},{"time":1139000,"text":"and then we had this bust."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1142000,"text":"All right, this is a technology"},{"time":1144000,"text":"that we put together using some of the technologies we're involved in."},{"time":1147000,"text":"This will be a routine feature in a cell phone."},{"time":1151000,"text":"It would be able to translate from one language to another."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1163000,"text":"So let me just end with a couple of scenarios."},{"time":1165000,"text":"By 2010 computers will disappear."},{"time":1169000,"text":"They'll be so small, they'll be embedded in our clothing, in our environment."},{"time":1172000,"text":"Images will be written directly to our retina,"},{"time":1174000,"text":"providing full-immersion virtual reality,"},{"time":1176000,"text":"augmented real reality. We'll be interacting with virtual personalities."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1180000,"text":"But if we go to 2029, we really have the full maturity of these trends,"},{"time":1184000,"text":"and you have to appreciate how many turns of the screw"},{"time":1187000,"text":"in terms of generations of technology, which are getting faster and faster, we'll have at that point."},{"time":1191000,"text":"I mean, we will have two-to-the-25th-power"},{"time":1193000,"text":"greater price performance, capacity and bandwidth"},{"time":1196000,"text":"of these technologies, which is pretty phenomenal."},{"time":1198000,"text":"It'll be millions of times more powerful than it is today."},{"time":1200000,"text":"We'll have completed the reverse-engineering of the human brain,"},{"time":1203000,"text":"1,000 dollars of computing will be far more powerful"},{"time":1206000,"text":"than the human brain in terms of basic raw capacity."},{"time":1210000,"text":"Computers will combine"},{"time":1212000,"text":"the subtle pan-recognition powers"},{"time":1214000,"text":"of human intelligence with ways in which machines are already superior,"},{"time":1217000,"text":"in terms of doing analytic thinking,"},{"time":1219000,"text":"remembering billions of facts accurately."},{"time":1221000,"text":"Machines can share their knowledge very quickly."},{"time":1223000,"text":"But it's not just an alien invasion of intelligent machines."},{"time":1228000,"text":"We are going to merge with our technology."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1230000,"text":"These nano-bots I mentioned"},{"time":1232000,"text":"will first be used for medical and health applications:"},{"time":1236000,"text":"cleaning up the environment, providing powerful fuel cells"},{"time":1239000,"text":"and widely distributed decentralized solar panels and so on in the environment."},{"time":1244000,"text":"But they'll also go inside our brain,"},{"time":1246000,"text":"interact with our biological neurons."},{"time":1248000,"text":"We've demonstrated the key principles of being able to do this."},{"time":1251000,"text":"So, for example,"},{"time":1253000,"text":"full-immersion virtual reality from within the nervous system,"},{"time":1255000,"text":"the nano-bots shut down the signals coming from your real senses,"},{"time":1258000,"text":"replace them with the signals that your brain would be receiving"},{"time":1261000,"text":"if you were in the virtual environment,"},{"time":1263000,"text":"and then it'll feel like you're in that virtual environment."},{"time":1265000,"text":"You can go there with other people, have any kind of experience"},{"time":1267000,"text":"with anyone involving all of the senses."},{"time":1270000,"text":"\"Experience beamers,\" I call them, will put their whole flow of sensory experiences"},{"time":1273000,"text":"in the neurological correlates of their emotions out on the Internet."},{"time":1276000,"text":"You can plug in and experience what it's like to be someone else."},{"time":1279000,"text":"But most importantly,"},{"time":1281000,"text":"it'll be a tremendous expansion"},{"time":1283000,"text":"of human intelligence through this direct merger with our technology,"},{"time":1287000,"text":"which in some sense we're doing already."},{"time":1289000,"text":"We routinely do intellectual feats"},{"time":1291000,"text":"that would be impossible without our technology."},{"time":1293000,"text":"Human life expectancy is expanding. It was 37 in 1800,"},{"time":1296000,"text":"and with this sort of biotechnology, nano-technology revolutions,"},{"time":1301000,"text":"this will move up very rapidly"},{"time":1303000,"text":"in the years ahead."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1305000,"text":"My main message is that progress in technology"},{"time":1309000,"text":"is exponential, not linear."},{"time":1312000,"text":"Many -- even scientists -- assume a linear model,"},{"time":1316000,"text":"so they'll say, \"Oh, it'll be hundreds of years"},{"time":1318000,"text":"before we have self-replicating nano-technology assembly"},{"time":1321000,"text":"or artificial intelligence.\""},{"time":1323000,"text":"If you really look at the power of exponential growth,"},{"time":1326000,"text":"you'll see that these things are pretty soon at hand."},{"time":1329000,"text":"And information technology is increasingly encompassing"},{"time":1332000,"text":"all of our lives, from our music to our manufacturing"},{"time":1336000,"text":"to our biology to our energy to materials."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1340000,"text":"We'll be able to manufacture almost anything we need in the 2020s,"},{"time":1343000,"text":"from information, in very inexpensive raw materials,"},{"time":1345000,"text":"using nano-technology."},{"time":1348000,"text":"These are very powerful technologies."},{"time":1350000,"text":"They both empower our promise and our peril."},{"time":1354000,"text":"So we have to have the will to apply them to the right problems."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1357000,"text":"Thank you very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1358000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}